pullRequest.body:
If the update fails, it will leave the PR open, preventing the action from creating more such PRs.

Also adds a workflow action that reports on zulip if one of these PRs fails.

nodes.body:
This targets master. 

Ideally this would use a separate secret token from `NIGHTLY_TESTING`, but I know that is set up with the right permissions to be able to push branches. 🤷‍♀️  If any maintainer would like to add extra secrets/tokens that would be fine.

This is usually run by me manually. It should be cheap to run, I don't see any downside to running it often.

As always, testing scheduled CI actions is very tricky, so I'm in favour of merging and fixing whatever issue there might be when it surfaces.

maintainer merge

So it will roughly double the number of daily commits to master, right? Not sure of the implications, I just find it surprising that you would do that.

> So it will roughly double the number of daily commits to master, right? Not sure of the implications, I just find it surprising that you would do that.

But it will only commit something if there is an interesting update to make, right? If all dependencies are up to date, nothing happens. Or am I misunderstanding some of the conditionals in the script?
Johan, that is my understanding as well.

> But it will only commit something if there is an interesting update to make, right? If all dependencies are up to date, nothing happens. Or am I misunderstanding some of the conditionals in the script?

Oh sure, it doesn't commit an empty update. But in general that means that roughly every commit to eg Batteries will get a corresponding update here. I guess that's not much of a problem since the scales of activity between the two repos are so different.

Anyway, I think my questions show that more comment would be welcome 😉

Let's try this out in production.

bors merge
